{
  "explanation": "The defendant, a first-time offender with no prior criminal history, committed a serious breach of trust by embezzling $25,000 from their employer. Mitigating factors include the absence of a prior record and the active effort to make restitution by partially paying back the stolen funds. While the offense warrants active incarceration to deter future financial crimes and reflect the breach of fiduciary duty, the defendant's rehabilitation potential and mitigating circumstances justify a sentence at the lower end of the sentencing range. The disruptive outburst from the courtroom spectator was dismissed as entirely irrelevant to the sentencing process. Therefore, an active sentence of 6 months of incarceration is deemed appropriate, to be followed by a period of supervised release and a strict schedule for full restitution.",
  "verdict": 6
}
